title: Hex Ball & Socket Z Axis Brakcet

description.text:
PROTOTYPE - Under testing! Hex ball & socket connection for 8mm diameter z axis lead screw. Made to replace oldham coupler in systems where the leadscrew is fixed only in two places - at the motor using a flexable coupler and at the load (x-axis). Fixes to 2020 Aluminium profile. Unlike the oldham, this connector allows the lead screw to change angle to accomodate say an offset in the motor coupler or a bent shaft. It also has the benefit of separating if the x axis carriage hits the bed (in a similar fashion to the oldham). The "Socket Original TT" should be a drop in replacement for the usual oldham coupler on the stock Tevo Tarantula fixed to the underside of the x-axis rail - the other "Socket" is for my modified machine.

Feedback much appreciated

title: Honda Shadow RS speedo bezel
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: I've had an issue with my speedometer face plate warping on my 2010 Honda Shadow RS. Honda says it's because of my aftermarket Memphis Shade windshield. But whatever the reason, I was getting sick of tearing everything apart and making new face plates all the time. So once I got my 3d printer, enough was enough. These two pieces replace the original chrome bezel (once you get it off). You still use all the rest of the speedometer components, like the rubber seals and trim. You just throw out the chrome bezel. Now you can tweak, mod, edit and fabricate to your hearts content without removing the speedo and having to pry the bezel off every time you feel like making a change. Just simply unscrew the new bezel, make your changes, and screw it back together. The speedo face in the picture is just a prototype, it's not complete yet, so I haven't uploaded that file. But it is made from white ABS, and it has seen plenty of sun and hasn't warped a bit! The bezel is made from Proto Pasta carbon fiber htpla. The color matches the rest of the speedo well, and it also hasn't melted or mis-shapen. I don't think this will work for speedometers that aren't mounted outside of the tank, but this may work for other models just by simply resizing your dimensions to fit your needs.

Last time I asked if there were any fans of Rick and Morty out there. It turns out there are! Rick got a lot of love, so let's give him some company. He redeemed his voucher for a replacement Morty.

I created this model in ZBrush. I used ZSpheres to get the main body shape there. I modeled him in an A pose, then I moved his arms to get them in the right position. Then I just went through, extracted the areas where his clothes are, then I shaped and added details to the face.

After modeling I ran it through Meshmixer to plane cut the feet so he'll stand normally. Then I also exported it in STL format from there. I printed it on my Wanhao D7 with FunToDo Snow White Resin.

Then my wife sanded and primed it. She used her airbrush to paint the skin colors on, then used paintbrushes and acrylic paints to paint everything else. Then we just super glued it to the base.

description.text:
I wanted to be able to mount a few spools of filament conveniently above my Anet A8 printer and was inspired bu a few other designs.

The bracket worked well and allowed me to use a wooden rod as the main shaft.
I also purchased some roller skate bearings, buy the cheapest ones you can from ebay.
I created some bearing covers to keep the spools from moving too.

After a few weeks I found that the filament I was using absorbed moisture and would no longer print. After drying it out in the oven for an hour, I purchase a plastic box and silicon jell to keep it dry.

The spool bracket is now used to hold up the box as show in the photo.

If you don't have the same problem as me the bracket work well.

(1/4 UNC)

if you use another cam with 1/4 UNC keep in mind the distance from the wall you mount to the edge of the plate the camera is attached to it is 25mm

Distance from Wall to the middle of the screw is 43mm

Logitech C615 has a moveable base so I had no need to build the mount flexible or moveable.

Update 2017/07/20<<<
Due to people which are interested in this and due to the fact that this mount could be used for every device which has a default "small" 1/4 UNC camera thread,
I added "Wallmount_Strong.stl"
The original wallmount is very thin and shouldn't be used for more than e.g. a Logitech C615.
Also you should make sure if you attach it to your enclosure that it is strong enough.
Due to the thin connection between wall and camera mount it would start swinging with negative effect on the picture of the cam if the enclosure e.g. is too leightweight and moves due to the printer movements.

Screws needed

M3x10 Screws used to attach the plate to the holder.
3,5x12 Spax used to attach the wallmount to the wall of the enclosure.

It sounds like you don't have the auto-probing stuff in the 'start g-code' section in slic3r perhaps. That area is for anything that you want to run before the actual model begins to print.
This is this bit from my stuff:
M109 S[first_layer_temperature_0];set extruder temp and start heating
G28 X0 Y0 ;home X and Y
G29 ;probe bed
G90; set absolute coordinates
G92 E0; reset extruder distance
G1 X10 Y10 F3000 ; move to back right corner
Everybody has a different way to do it though. Sounds like the cmartrap config in github doesn't do that. You don't actually have to autoprobe for every print. description.text:
As I usually carry with me some 18650 batteries (and I don't want any accidental shortcircuits), I designed a keychain holster for them. Print in flex material like ninjaflex or filaflex. Some day I was given one comercial silicone version of this as a gift, but as this is a very simple design (less than 10 minutes) I did my own.

Wasn't sure if my printer could handle this flex height without support, but IT DID! (a bit tricky, remember that the print tends to be bent by the hotend while printing, so use low speed like 15mm/s) No support required, bridging should be ok with minor postprocessing. Pic is for a black ninjaflex build, holds the batts pretty good.

Enjoy!

HINT: You can Z-scale up it a bit for some longer batts, or XY-scale up a bit for thicker batts. The STL is for a regular unprotected, flat top batt but can hold others due to elasticity.

TODO: Maybe a customizable version to allow for different kinds of batteries and/or multiple number of batteries. We'll see...

description.text:
I didn't have much of a need for a fan duct, but after removing my original plate steel duct I was surprised by how much it weighed. I decided to kill two birds with one stone and make a new fan duct that was more effective and lighter weight than the original.

This modification is a direct swap for the original, and will use the same fan, even if you're short on cable length.

I've also included a 0.4mm spacer in case you want to drop it down a bit. Stock should have a couple of millimetres clearance from the printbed and because the duct is directed downwards slightly this is fine.

Results are remarkably good. See the test print comparison. The rubbish one is the normal vent. In fact, these results were so good I'm wondering if my cooling fan was misbehaving in the rubbish print (same gcode for both prints).

The existing screws may be a tight fit. You may have to run a 2.5mm drill bit through the holes first. I decided I'd rather have them too tight than too loose.

description.text:
Chinese Brush Strokes "Eternity"
This is a Paintbrush carriage I have made to house 31 UltraViolet Leds, it is attached to a S2 Scribbler Parallax robot producing a neat way to scribe Chinese characters, using strokes with leading and/or trailing swoops, single lines and any combination to suit....
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-zfu0Vltgwk&feature=share&list=UUcxve9G8bHCBBKE5kaW_okg
...The Robot traverses a Phosphorescent vinyl sheet ... which soaks up Ultraviolet light like ink into blotting paper.... leaving behind a very "Jade" coloured painting. The Paint Brush is made from essentially 31 x 3mm UltraViolet Leds arranged in 4 groups which can be switched ON/OFF individually via the S2s Hacker Port. NB. I have added an extra "MakerBot" logo which can be attached to the Led carriage and use it as a stemple to cast Makerbot brands under robot control onto the Phosphor screen....

This project requires the following Materials :-
31 x 3mm Ultraviolet leds with the base of them sanded flush to the body (as the leds are tightly packed together)
1 x S2 scribbler robot available from Parallax.com
The leds are soldered together in groups
(1) single central led
(2) a 6 led ring surrounding the above (1)
(3) a 12 led ring surrounding the above (2)
(4) a 12 led ring surrounding the above (3) This is the basic set up.... For more details please find detailed instructions here :-
http://forums.parallax.com/showthread.php/153652-S2-Parallax-Scribbler-UV-series...-Part-3-of-5-Chinese-Brush-Strokes-quot-Eternity-quot

This replica is the famous BT 334 nuclear missile delivery vehicle. Designed around a nine 100 megaton nuclear missile launcher, it can obliterate a huge area. Normally used in a pattern of 3 x 3 square miles it could destroy large areas and exterminate any enemy not protected by shielding.
The missile have a long range (to 300 miles) and can be independently targeted as required. The vehicle is proof against hostile or irradiated atmosphere with its airlock entry point. Normally the crew carried are three, a driver, a missile operator and a commander. The vehicle has no secondary weapon system and generally is accompanied by a BT331 or similar vehicle as an escort.
The wheel system allows it to move over very difficult terrain with each double wheel pod being individually powered and steered, and can be jettisoned if damaged by a mine (or similar). The top speed is limited but the power from the double linked nuclear generators allows it almost unlimited range and very strong double linked shield system.
The official name is the "Grid Reaper", but in the field they are sometimes called a "Slam dunk".
Compared to the normal tanks produced at the same time, few of these were made, but when used they could unload an intense firepower on an enemy. Each missile was ten times the destructive power of a nuke cannon shell and three times the range. The missiles could also be independently targeted and their target changed inflight unlike the cannon shell.

description.text:
To get the most out of your SLA printed parts, UV-Curing is important.

The newly announced «Form Cure» by Formlabs (https://formlabs.com/de/tools/wash-cure/) treats finished prints with UV-LED lights for 60min by 80ºC and one rotation/min. And is quite expensive.

Here is the formlabs whitepaper about UV-curing: http://bit.ly/2vjm2CX

There are already some cool DIY Projects involving UV-Nail-Curing Devices, mine is just another one - it's quick and cheap to produce and ist's easy to use and has a nice, sleek look.

made at zurich universtiy of the arts - industrial design
https://www.zhdk.ch/ba-design-industrial-design-65

• I used OnShape.com and the files are public! Go make your own adjustments! http://bit.ly/2vC3Y6k (you needa free account...)
    Especially the material-thickness can be easily adjusted with the #mdf variable on top of the feature tree.

  • I downloaded the plans as DXF and CNC-milled them from an A2 sized MDF-sheet (12mm) with a 6mm tool.
  • I assembled everything and used a 10mm bolt as the main axis and two 8mm bolds as end-stops.
  • I mounted the two UV-Nail-Devices using 4 Zip-ties, tighten them together.

UV-Curing Chamber dimensions (without turntable): 150mm150mm170mm

• two UV-Nail-Curing Deviced (Bridge-shaped)
    I got these (LED): http://bit.ly/2uyze9u
    but amazon has similar ones that fit as well (bulbs, $19.99): http://amzn.to/2vCcKkB
  • one solar-powered turntable ($4.99): http://amzn.to/2u8eIJX
  • an A2 size MDF-sheet (12mm) or a similar Wood/Acrylic-sheet for CNC-milling or laser cutting
  • 1 M10 screw (45mm depending on material thickness)
  • 2 M8 screws (45mm depending on material thickness)
  • optional, but nice: a countdown timer to cut power after 60min: http://bit.ly/2uano42

if you buy smart and get your hands on a cnc/laser maschine, you can build this for under 50$

So here is a solution - quite universal clamp that keeps remote firmly but safely, and you can use GoPro compatible mount as well as design something for yourself.
I have used CA glue to join both parts, but there is also a place for 2 screws if you don't trust the glue.
Have fun, and fly safely!

description.text:
Introduction:

When printing my Z braces for the Plus, I found that it was a bunch of "take this part from here, this part from there, etc." and I ended up printing some parts I didn't need. Therefore, I decided to remix the parts I used into a "one stop shop".

You will need to print:

  • 4 of the BallsMk2
  • 1 of everything else

I note that I did not bother with the nut plugs, so I don't know if they will actually work. I've included them for completeness.

You will need the following hardware:

  • 2 pieces 5/16 or 8mm threaded rod at least 16.5" long (approx 420mm). I used 18" long pieces (457mm) because 36in (914mm) is a common length in the US.
  • 2 nylock nuts in the above width and thread.
  • 6 regular nuts in the above width and thread.
  • 4 M5 x 10 screws (for the front and rear corner feet, replacing the stock screws, which are too short)
  • 8 M3 x 10 screws (for the top left and right corners, replacing the stock screws, which are too short)

Instructions:

  1. With some pliers, pop out the the round plug, in the middle of the ball, which is is for support and it will pull out cleanly with needle nose pliers; so you do not need to enable support in your slicer for the balls.
  2. Undo the 4 screws on one side of the gantry and put on that side top bracket with 4 of the M3 x 10 screws. Try to get the corner back in the original position, because you don't want to knock your gantry out of square.
  3. Repeat step 1 for the other side.
  4. Undo the left and right rear screws (leaving the center one alone) and put on the two back feet using 2 M5 x 10 screws.
  5. Take your threaded rod and thread a regular nut on to it, and fit it into one of the front feet so that the threaded rod protrudes past the bottom of the foot.
  6. Add a nylock nut to the end of the rod so the flat part faces the interior of the foot.
  7. Pull the rod up so that the nut seats inside the foot.
  8. Tighten down on the regular nut so the foot is tight.
  9. From the other end of the threaded rod, add another regular nut and one of the balls. The ball should cover the nut, and you want it to go down far enough to give you enough space to get the rod through the bracket on the gantry.
  10. Remove the screw from the front corner appropriate to where you are going to install the foot.
  11. Sliding the threaded rod up through the top bracket, install the foot.
  12. As you are sliding the threaded rod in to the upper support, add a ball and a regular nut, as you won't have clearance to screw them on once everything is tight.
  13. Once the foot is in place, use an M5 x 10 screw to screw it down.
  14. Repeat the above steps for the opposite side bracket.
  15. Once both brackets are on and the balls containing the nuts can be turned freely, loosen the screws at the bottom of the gantry (the ones you had to put in when you first got the printer) and use the balls to square up the printer, tightening them at the end. Then tighten down the screws.

Now everything should be good and square.

description.text: This activity gives students a way to visually see and work with a tree diagram hands-on to understand the different outcomes a tree diagram represents in a given sample space.

Although there are many "things" for this activity, designing the manipulatives was fairly simple. First, I made a "one story house" by making a short rectangle. Then, for the "two story house" i made another rectangle that was double the height of the shorter rectangle. (Figure 1)

Then I made 3 copies of both the short and tall rectangles. For both the short and tall rectangles I added on three different shape roofs to the top of the rectangles (then grouped them together) : pyramid, roof (triangular prism), and round roof. (Figure 2)

Then I made two copies for each of these six houses. For the first set of copies, I made houses with one rectangular window. I did this by using the box hole feature to make an indent in the houses. (Figure 3)

For the second set of copies, I made houses with two square windows. I did this the same way by using the box hole feature to make the indents. (Figure 4)

Figure 1 Figure 2 Figure 3 Figure 4
CCSS

This activity will satisfy the following common core learning standards:
CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.7.SP.C.8
Find probabilities of compound events using organized lists, tables, tree diagrams, and simulation.

• This activity should be done after a brief introduction to tree diagrams *
    To start, split up the students into groups of 2-4. Each group will get a bag of the 20 "houses" that you've created. The students will be instructed to create their own 3-D Tree Diagram to represent all of the different houses that can be made when being able to choose from: a one story house or a two story house, a triangular "standard" roof or a round roof or a pyramid roof, and then either one window or two windows.
    • This will require a decent amount of space per group, so the students can either work on large tables, combined desks, or the floor. If available, perhaps using large poster boards or large personal whiteboards may be helpful for the students to place their diagram on. They would also be helpful for the students to draw their "branches" in the tree diagram to connect their items. However, if these are not available you can use any kind of stick/string such as pipe cleaners for the students to use as branches. Walk around and check in with each group to ensure they are understanding and creating their tree-digram properly/accurately. Regroup after every group has completed the activity and have the students share how many different houses there could be (each group should have the same answer).

The only materials needed for this activity are the "things" that you have created. You may want to supply either a large poster board or large whiteboard for the groups of students do that they can draw in their branches, but it is optional. If those are not used, you will have to supply some kind of "stick"/string such as pipe cleaners for the students to use as branches.

title: Airsoft Magpul ASAP adapter spacer for Lancer Tactical AR15

description.text:
This will adapt an Magpul ASAP (or clone) to the Lancer Tactical AR15/M4. My model specifically is LT-03T-G2.

The buttstock collar tube lock and where it mounts on the Lancer unit has a smaller inside diameter than the actual firearm. This makes a mismatch for the ASAP sling replacement part because its inside diameter is a few mm bigger.

To make up for this discrepancy, I just designed a spacer that matches the outside diameter and design of the Lancer upper and inside diameter of the ASAP sling mount.

Its tight, but should fit with only hand pressure. I beveled the inside of the spacer to assist with fitment. No locating pins are necessary because it is part of the spacer.

This may fit other airsoft guns, but this is the only one I have. The photos should help you determine if it will fit a non-Lancer gun.
